National Directorate of Employment (NDE) has commenced the training of 750 youths for Basic National Open Apprenticeship Scheme (B- NOAS) for self-reliance. The state coordinator, Alhaji Abubakar Liman who made the disclosure while flagging off the scheme yesterday in Minna, said the scheme targets rural areas. He said that the informal sector is necessary to enhance development and economic growth hence the need for the scheme to be focused on the sector by the agency. According to him,  the 750 beneficiaries consisted of youths and women who were trained in diverse skills and they cut across  the 25 local government areas in Niger State. He therefore charged the participants to be dedicated and pay attention to the training in order to improve themselves, their families and the society. He applauded the director general, Dr Nasir Mohammad Ladan for the transformation of the agency in the last few years in job creation. The director general, Dr Nasir Mohammad Ladan represented by a director, Mrs Agnes Ogbada reiterated the commitment of NDE in touching the lives of rural dwellers in the country. He told the participants to make effective use of the opportunity by concentrating on what they will learn during the training exercise. The state permanent secretary, Ministry of Youths, Hajiya Jumai Idris assured of the partnership with the agency and relevant sectors in creating jobs for the unemployed youths in the state. She charged the beneficiaries to avail themselves of the opportunity and urged them to shun all kinds of social vices so as to be law-abiding citizens.